A Regression Analysis on Professional Tennis Athletes' Rank based on their Height and Age

By: Johnny, Nicole, Rodrigo, and Sophie

Introduction:

 Tennis is an extremely popular sport that requires a multitude of skills like footwork, power, and flexibility. However, to what extent is tennis a sport that can be learned and practiced rather than a sport that's reliant on ones genetics and age? Typically, those who are taller have an advantage in tennis as they can serve faster and more effectively. In addition to this, the prime ages of tennis success are between the ages of 21-29 and this is relevant knowledge for those pursuing tennis as a professional career. The main goal of our regression analysis is to see if we can create an accurate model that predicts a professional tennis athletes success in the field of tennis based on their age and height. Our main question in regards to this data set, is can we predict the current rank of a tennis athlete according to their age and height?

Our Dataset :

 We are using the Player Stats for the top 500 players dataset. The dataset includes information on a number of professional tennis players, including their height, age, dominant hand, current rank, best rank, price money, country and several other variables. The columns we will be extracting and using for a regression model are height, age and current rank.

#tidying up our data

tidyed_up_data <- tennis_data |>
rename(current_rank = 'Current Rank') |>
select(current_rank, Height, Age) |>

#splitting the current rank column into a column of current rank and a column of current total points

separate(col = 'current_rank',
        into = c("current_rank", "Points"),
        sep = " ") |>

#splitting the Age observations into a column of Age (years) and a column of the dated birthday

separate(col = 'Age',
        into = c("Age", "Year"),
        sep = " ") |>

#omiting all columns but current_rank, height, age

select(`current_rank`, Height, Age) |>

#remove the cm in observation of the column height

mutate(Height = gsub(" cm", "", Height)) |>
na.omit(df[, "Height"])

 The Current Rank column was renamed as current_rank for ease when graphing and we selected the columns, current_rank, Height, Age as these were the categories we wanted to explore.

In[32]:
#creating the recipe

tennis_recipe <- recipe(current_rank ~ Age + Height, data = tennis_train) |>
step_scale(all_predictors()) |>
step_center(all_predictors())

  The recipe function is used to preprocess the tennis training dataset. In the recipe, the "current_rank ~ Age + Height" argument specifies that the current_rank variable is used as the response, and both age and height are used as the predictors. Step_scale and step_center are added to the recipe for scaling and centering the predictor variables. Using all_predictors() indicates that scaling and centering should be applied to all the predictor variables. After scaling and centering, all predictor variables would have mean = 0 and standard deviation = 1. We want to scale and center our data to make sure that age and height are equally weighted in predicting the current rank variable.
In[33]:
#creating the model

tennis_spec <- nearest_neighbor(weight_func = "rectangular", neighbors = tune()) |>
set_engine("kknn") |>
set_mode("regression")

 The nearest_neighbor function is used to create a model specification for K-nearest neighbor classification. By specifying weight_func = rectangular", this ensures votes from each neighboring point are weighted equally. Neighbors are specified using tune() to indicate that a range of K values will be tested. In the set_engine function,  kknn is specified as it is the R package used to build the regression model. In the set_mode function, regression is specified as the type of method that will be worked with.
In[34]:
##vfold split to find best k value

tennis_vfold <- vfold_cv(tennis_train, v = 5, strata = current_rank)

  The vfold_cv function splits the tennis training set into evenly sized chunks and by specifying v=5, the training set would be split into 5 chunks to perform 5-fold cross validation.
In[35]:
gridvals <- tibble(neighbors = seq(1,61, by = 1))

 The tibble function is used to create a new dataframe with a column named neighbors that contains the range of K values to be tested. seq(1,61, by=1) states that values from 1 to 61 will be tested in cross validation.
In[36]:
#finding the best k value

tennis_multi_graph <- workflow() |>
add_recipe(tennis_recipe) |>
add_model(tennis_spec) |>
tune_grid(tennis_vfold, grid = gridvals) |>
collect_metrics() |>
filter(.metric == "rmse")

 A data analysis workflow is created using workflow(), then adding in the recipe and model created earlier using the tennis training data set. The tune_grid function is used to fit the model for each of the values listed in the data frame created earlier that contains the range of K values to be tested. The collect_metrics function combines mean and standard error for the RMPSE values obtained across the 5 folds for each K value. Lastly, we filter for RMPSE values for each K value.

In[40]:
tennis_spec_2 <- nearest_neighbor(weight_func = "rectangular", neighbors = tennis_k_value) |>
set_engine("kknn") |>
set_mode("regression")

 A new model specification is created using the same nearest_neighbor function, but this time the model is trained with neighbors = tennis_k_value which is the K value with the lowest estimated RMPSE from 5-fold cross-validation. In the set_engine function, kknn is specified as it is the R package used to build the regression model. In the set_mode function, regression is specified as the type of method that will be worked with.
In[41]:
tennis_multi_fit <- workflow() |>
add_recipe(tennis_recipe) |>
add_model(tennis_spec_2) |>
fit(data = tennis_train)

 A data analysis workflow is created using workflow(), we add in the recipe created earlier and our re-trained model. The tennis training dataset is fitted into the whole workflow.

Discussion of the Results:

 Looking at our regression line, we see that its fairly linear with some inconsistencies such as vertical lines. The linearity of our regression doesn't show to be a positive or negative relationship as the line is fairly even/flat. Both the age and height variable predict the current rank of an athlete to be somewhere near 150.

 We can say that our regression line is not a good predictor for current rank. The regression line predicts all professional athletes of different heights and ages to have a current rank at around 150. There can be only 20 people between the ranks 140-160, so having everyone being predicted there tells us there isn't a strong relationship between our predictor variables and current rank. To put it into context of someone using our model, we know the ranks go from 1 to 500. If someone wanted to look at what type of player would have a rank in the 400-500 range, they would see that our regression model has predicted everyone to be around 150. 

 Another example of our shortcomings with this regression model is looking at specific people in our dataset. We see through the final graphs that the two people (potentially the same person) who are the shortest and youngest in our training data seems to have a very high rank (somewhere in the top 20). However as we know from our regression line, it would predict that someone that young or that short would still have a rank of about 150.
 Initially, our group thought that it would make sense for someone who is younger and taller to have an advantage as a professional athlete. However, when we look at our ggpairs plot, we see that the correlation coefficient between our predictor variables and current rank is close to 0. The coefficient between age and height vs current rank tells us that there is little to no linear relationship that exists between our predictor variables and current rank. That reveleation allowed us to expect that our regression line would not be the most effective in predicting current rank.

Impact of our Findings:

 Our findings can impact peoples understanding of tennis as a sport. One can now know that age and height does not make one's success in the world of professional tennis. The idea of practice makes perfect may be the only factor to success in professional tennis or there are other biological factors out there that affect one's success.

What Future Questions could our Project lead to?:

 The results of our analysis showed that our chosen factors weren't the best predictors for rank. This leads to questions of whether there are other biological/physical features of a person that we didn't consider. Maybe a variable like wingspan is a good predictor of a professional tennis athlete's success. However, If other biological factors show the same correlation to rank as our variables did, does that mean tennis is a sport where practice can always lead to success?

 We should also think about what the dataset was about. What if we did this analysis again on regular people and not professional athletes? Maybe the practice that professional athletes go through level the playing field for success despite biolgical advantages. If we looked at a bunch of people with no tennis experience at all, it may show that factors like height and age do come into play in one's success against other inexperienced people.
